otes -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis innovative volume will be welcomed by moral and political philosophers, social scientists, and anyone who reflects seriously on the twentieth century's heavy burden of war, genocide, ethnic cleansing, and other evidence of people's desire to harm one another. María Pía Lara brings together a provocative set of essays that reexamine evil in the context of a "postmetaphysical" world, a world that no longer equates natural and human evil and no longer believes in an omnipotent God. The question of how and why God permits evil events to occur is replaced by the question of how and why humans perform radically evil acts.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGood and evil. 4aEthics & Moral Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh1 aAlexander, Jeffrey C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAllison, Henry E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernstein, Carol L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernstein, Richard J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCabrera, Isabel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCooke, Maeve, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCruz, Manuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDews, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerrara, Alessandro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFine, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLara, María Pía, econtributor.4ctb